Author:  LAING & BLACKWELL
Vol / Page:  246] p. 258
Edition:
Quote:  In bush clearings, [<i>Aristotelia serrata (The Wineberry</i>)] is one of the first plants to come up, and would, on this account, be termed by the Americans a `fireweed.' ...It goes by different names in different districts. In Otago, it is the New Zealand Currant, or Moko-mok'. In Canterbury, it is called the Wine-berry. In the North Island, it is the Mako-mako.
